05526nam a22008175i 9780857455475DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20082008nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574554757 a10.1515/97808574554752doi  a(DE-B1597)636562  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aE65b.I476 2009 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a323.11970800aIndigenous Peoples, Civil Society, and the Neo-liberal State in Latin America /ced. by Edward F. Fischer. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2008] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Indigenous Peoples, Neo-liberal Regimes, and Varieties of Civil Society in Latin America -- tChapter 1 Indigenous Politics and the State: The Andean Highlands in the Nineteenth and Twentieth Centuries -- tChapter 2 La Mano Dura and the Violence of Civil Society in Bolivia -- tChapter 3 Empire/Multitude—State/Civil Society: Rethinking Topographies of Power through Transnational Connectivity in Ecuador and Beyond -- tChapter 4 The Power of Ecuador’s Indigenous Communities in an Era of Cultural Pluralism -- tChapter 5 Civil Society and the Indigenous Movement in Colombia: The Consejo Regional Indígena del Cauca -- tChapter 6 Indigenous Nations in Guatemalan Democracy and the State: A Tentative Assessment -- tChapter 7 Reformulating the Guatemalan State: The Role of Maya Intellectuals and Civil Society Discourse -- tChapter 8 El otro lado: Local Ends and Development in a Q’eqchi’ Maya Community -- tChapter 9 The Political Uses of Maya Medicine: Civil Organizations in Chiapas and the Ventriloquism Effect -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn recent years the concept and study of “civil society” has received a lot of attention from political scientists, economists, and sociologists, but less so from anthropologists. A ground-breaking ethnographic approach to civil society as it is formed in indigenous communities in Latin America, this volume explores the multiple potentialities of civil society’s growth and critically assesses the potential for sustained change. Much recent literature has focused on the remarkable gains made by civil society and the chapters in this volume reinforce this trend while also showing the complexity of civil society - that civil society can itself sometimes be uncivil. In doing so, these insightful contributions speak not only to Latin American area studies but also to the changing shape of global systems of political economy in general.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aCivil societyzLatin America. 0aIndiansxGovernment relations. 0aIndiansxSocial conditions. 0aIndians, Treatment ofzLatin America. 0aNeoliberalismzLatin America. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aAchá, Gloria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaud, Michiel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCasaús Arzú, Marta Elena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCojtí Cuxil, Demetrio, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColloredo-Mansfeld, Rudi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDickins, Avery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Edward F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischer, Edward F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGoldstein, Daniel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHinojosa, Eric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPitarch, Pedro